29 Oct 2009 23:29






I have an edit to make, but I'm worried about the specifics and whether I'm overstepping my bounds. It has a reference to the isolation chamber being sealed against "insects." Spiders aren't insects. Simplest thing would be simply to change it to arachnids, which isn't a huge change… but I figure that it'd probably not just be proofed against arachnids, but terrestrial arthropods in general — insects, arachnids, and the suborder Oniscidea of Order Isopoda (better known as woodlice), which contains the only fully-terrestrial crustaceans — "terrestrial" crabs are actually semiterrestrial, and require water for reproduction.

The issue here is that altering it to "terrestrial arthropods", although the most accurate, is:

a) Relatively obtuse.

b) May be a large enough alteration to the substance of the article to be above a "go ahead and edit" level — as although it's likely what was originally intended, it substantially changes the actual content of that passage.







